Steps 1-3 should be done immediately — they are low-effort, high-impact fixes
that close the worst escalation paths. Steps 4-8 form a second batch. Steps
9-13 are cleanup. Step 14 (profile scoping) is the largest piece and should
be a deliberate architectural decision.

Total estimated effort (excluding step 14): ~7-8 hours of implementation +
testing. Step 14 adds 2-3 days depending on which option is chosen.


================================================================================
  PART III — AUTHORIZATION MODEL EVALUATION
================================================================================

Evaluation of the current permission/authorization architecture for robustness,
ease of application, and runtime efficiency. Performed 2026-03-23.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
10. ARCHITECTURE OVERVIEW
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The model has four dimensions, layered bottom-to-top:

  Layer 4  │ Feature override    │ AdminFeaturePermission (per-admin, per-feature)
  Layer 3  │ Base role defaults  │ ADMIN → all features; READ_ONLY → export/reports
  Layer 2  │ Profile access      │ AdminProfileRole (admin × profile × base role)
  Layer 1  │ Directory access    │ "has role in ANY profile in this directory"
  Layer 0  │ Principal type      │ SecurityConfig: SUPERADMIN / ADMIN / SELF_SERVICE

Enforcement is split across three mechanisms:
  - SecurityConfig  — URL-pattern matching, coarse role check (layer 0)
  - @PreAuthorize   — Spring Security SpEL on controller methods (layer 0)
  - @RequiresFeature + AOP aspect — directory + feature check (layers 1-4)

Key files:
  - auth/AuthPrincipal.java              — immutable JWT-derived principal
  - auth/PermissionService.java          — 4-dimension permission logic
  - auth/FeaturePermissionAspect.java    — AOP interceptor for @RequiresFeature
  - auth/RequiresFeature.java            — annotation definition
  - auth/DirectoryId.java                — parameter marker for aspect
  - config/SecurityConfig.java           — global filter chain + URL rules
  - entity/enums/FeatureKey.java         — 17 feature permission keys
  - entity/enums/BaseRole.java           — ADMIN, READ_ONLY
  - entity/AdminProfileRole.java         — admin × profile assignment
  - entity/AdminFeaturePermission.java   — per-admin feature overrides

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
11. ROBUSTNESS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Strengths:

  a) AuthPrincipal is immutable.
     A Java record derived from cryptographically-signed JWT claims. No DB hit
     during authentication. Cannot be tampered with post-issuance. Role, account
     ID, and username are all embedded in the token.

  b) Feature override model (layer 4) is well-designed.
     Explicit enable/disable per-admin per-feature, with base-role defaults as
     fallback. This gives fine-grained control without requiring a row for every
     admin × feature combination. The READONLY_DEFAULT_FEATURES set
     (BULK_EXPORT, REPORTS_RUN, REPORTS_EXPORT) is appropriately conservative —
     all truly read-only operations.

  c) Superadmin controllers are consistently locked down.
     All 6 controllers under /superadmin/ use class-level
     @PreAuthorize("hasRole('SUPERADMIN')"). No exceptions, no leaks.

  d) No ad-hoc SecurityContextHolder usage.
     Only FeaturePermissionAspect and JwtAuthenticationFilter touch the
     SecurityContext directly. Controllers use @AuthenticationPrincipal
     injection. No scattered manual principal extraction.

Weaknesses:

  e) Three competing authorization mechanisms with no enforced convention.
     Of 22 controllers:
       - 6 use @RequiresFeature (with @DirectoryId)
       - 8 use @PreAuthorize
       - 4 use neither (relying on SecurityConfig catch-all)
       - 4 mix approaches within the same controller

     Within the same URL hierarchy (/api/v1/directories/{id}/...), some
     endpoints are feature-gated and some aren't. There is no enforced rule
     for when to use which mechanism. Every new endpoint is a judgment call
     that can silently go wrong.

  f) The SecurityConfig catch-all is too permissive as a safety net.
     Line 84: .requestMatchers("/api/v1/**").hasAnyRole("SUPERADMIN", "ADMIN")
     Any endpoint that forgets to add @PreAuthorize or @RequiresFeature is
     still reachable by any admin. A deny-by-default posture would be safer:
     require explicit annotation, reject at startup if missing.

  g) READ endpoints are systematically unprotected.
     UserController.search(), GroupController.search(), SchemaController.*,
     DirectoryBrowseController.browse() — none have feature gates. Any admin
     with access to any profile in a directory can enumerate all users, groups,
     and schema objects. This is inconsistent with AccessReviewController,
     which requires ACCESS_REVIEW_MANAGE even for listing campaigns.

  h) Layer 1 (directory access) is a blunt instrument.
     existsByAdminAccountIdAndProfileDirectoryId() grants access if the admin
     has a role in ANY profile. This collapses all profile boundaries into a
     single directory-level gate (covered in detail in Part I).

  i) @PreAuthorize and @RequiresFeature don't compose.
     They are parallel systems. @PreAuthorize checks role from JWT.
     @RequiresFeature checks directory access + feature from DB. If an
     endpoint needs both "must be SUPERADMIN" AND "must have feature X", you
     must use both annotations or bury one check in service code (as
     AccessReviewController.create() does). There is no unified annotation.

  j) No compile-time or startup-time enforcement.
     If a developer adds a new @PostMapping and forgets @RequiresFeature, the
     code compiles, tests pass (unless there's a specific auth test), and the
     endpoint silently falls through to the catch-all. No annotation processor,
     no startup scan, no "every endpoint must have at least one auth
     annotation" check.

Robustness rating: MODERATE
  The individual pieces (JWT, feature overrides, superadmin lockdown) are solid.
  The weakness is structural: three parallel mechanisms with no enforced
  convention, making it easy to leave gaps when adding new endpoints.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
12. EASE OF APPLICATION
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Strengths:

  a) @RequiresFeature is ergonomic when used.
     One annotation, one enum value, automatic directoryId extraction via
     @DirectoryId. A developer adding a new endpoint writes:
       @RequiresFeature(FeatureKey.USER_CREATE)
     and gets directory access + feature permission checking for free. The AOP
     aspect handles everything. This is the model's strongest design point.

  b) FeatureKey enum is self-documenting.
     17 values with dot-notation DB representation. Adding a new feature is:
     add an enum value, annotate the endpoint, done. The JPA converter handles
     serialization transparently.

  c) @DirectoryId fallback to parameter name is a nice ergonomic touch.
     Existing code without the annotation still works via the "directoryId"
     parameter name convention in FeaturePermissionAspect.

Weaknesses:

  d) Three different places to check when auditing an endpoint.
     To understand what's actually enforced on any given endpoint, a reviewer
     must check:
       1. SecurityConfig URL patterns (global)
       2. @PreAuthorize on controller class or method
       3. @RequiresFeature on method
     All three can be present, absent, or contradictory. This is error-prone
     for code review and security audits.

  e) No clear rule for when to use which mechanism.
     The codebase has no documented convention. Observed heuristics:
       - Superadmin-only endpoints → @PreAuthorize("hasRole('SUPERADMIN')")
       - Feature-gated write endpoints → @RequiresFeature
       - Read endpoints → nothing (catch-all)
       - Playbooks → @PreAuthorize("hasAnyRole('ADMIN', 'SUPERADMIN')")
     But these are inconsistently applied and undocumented.

  f) requireProfileAccess() is barely used.
     It exists in PermissionService but almost nothing calls it. Most code uses
     requireDirectoryAccess or requireFeature (which internally calls
     requireDirectoryAccess). If a developer wants to scope an operation to a
     specific profile, they have to know to call requireProfileAccess()
     manually — and there is no annotation equivalent like @RequiresProfile.

  g) No feature permission matrix documentation.
     The mapping of features to endpoints is implicit (scattered across
     @RequiresFeature annotations). An admin configuring feature overrides
     must guess which features gate which operations. A superadmin setting up
     a READ_ONLY admin has no reference for what they'll actually be able to
     do beyond the three default features.

  h) Mixed authorization in same controller is confusing.
     AccessReviewController: most methods use @RequiresFeature, but create()
     adds a manual isSuperadmin() check inside the method body.
     GroupController: write methods use @RequiresFeature, read methods use
     nothing. UserController: same pattern. A developer extending these
     controllers has no consistent template to follow.

Ease of application rating: MIXED
  @RequiresFeature is well-designed and easy to use. But the lack of a single
  enforced mechanism, plus undocumented conventions and three places to check,
  means developers need tribal knowledge to apply authorization correctly.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
13. RUNTIME EFFICIENCY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Strengths:

  a) JWT validation is zero-cost to the database.
     JwtTokenService.parse() is pure cryptographic signature verification.
     Role, account ID, and username are embedded in the token. Authentication
     never touches the database.

  b) @PreAuthorize is zero-cost to the database.
     Role checks come from the JWT-derived authority set already in the
     SecurityContext. No additional query.

  c) AdminFeaturePermissionRepository is well-indexed.
     Explicit idx_afp_admin on admin_account_id, plus unique constraint on
     (admin_account_id, feature_key). Feature override lookups are fast.

Weaknesses:

  d) 3 DB queries per @RequiresFeature request, with zero caching.
     Every request hitting a @RequiresFeature endpoint triggers:

       Query 1: existsByAdminAccountIdAndProfileDirectoryId()
                → directory access check (join: admin_profile_roles → profiles)
       Query 2: findByAdminAccountIdAndFeatureKey()
                → feature override lookup
       Query 3: findAllByAdminAccountId()
                → base role fallback (conditional — only if no override found)

     These are small queries, but they execute on every single request. For a
     tool where admins do rapid user lookups or process bulk operations, this
     accumulates. An admin browsing a user list triggers 3 DB round-trips
     before the LDAP query even starts.

  e) No permission caching at any level.
     No @Cacheable, no CacheManager, no request-scoped cache. An admin's
     profile roles and feature overrides change rarely (only when a superadmin
     reconfigures them), yet they are re-queried on every API call.

     A simple request-scoped cache (load once per HTTP request, reuse within
     that request) would eliminate redundant queries when multiple permission
     checks occur in the same request. A short-TTL application-level cache
     (e.g. 60 seconds via Caffeine) would reduce DB load further, at the cost
     of slightly delayed permission changes.

  f) Missing index on admin_profile_roles.admin_account_id.
     The existsByAdminAccountIdAndProfileDirectoryId() query (Query 1 — the
     hottest path) joins admin_profile_roles → provisioning_profiles to check
     directory_id. The only index is the unique constraint on
     (admin_account_id, profile_id). For admins with many profiles across
     directories, this may degrade to a sequential scan on the join.

     Fix: CREATE INDEX idx_apr_admin ON admin_profile_roles(admin_account_id);

  g) findAllByAdminAccountId() in Query 3 is over-fetched.
     It loads ALL profile roles for the admin across ALL directories just to
     check if any has BaseRole.ADMIN. A simple exists query would suffice:

       existsByAdminAccountIdAndBaseRole(UUID adminId, BaseRole role)

     This avoids transferring unnecessary rows and simplifies the logic from
     a stream().anyMatch() to a boolean return.

  h) No batch optimization for multi-operation requests.
     Playbook execution calls execute() per target DN. Each invocation
     re-runs the full 3-query permission check. For a playbook targeting 50
     users, that's 150 permission queries. A batch-aware permission check
     (validate once, execute many) would reduce this to 3 queries total.

Efficiency rating: ADEQUATE but wasteful
  Works fine for low-volume admin usage. Would degrade under high-concurrency
  scenarios (bulk operations, many admins). The fixes are straightforward:
  add one index, add one cache, fix one over-fetch.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
14. AUTHORIZATION CONSISTENCY ANALYSIS
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Distribution of authorization mechanisms across 22 controllers:

  Mechanism                               │ Controllers │ Count
  ────────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────┼──────
  @RequiresFeature only                   │ AccessReview, BulkGroup,     │  6
                                          │ BulkUser, ScheduledReport,   │
                                          │ User (writes), Group (writes)│
  @PreAuthorize only                      │ All 6 superadmin controllers,│  8
                                          │ LifecyclePlaybook,           │
                                          │ ProvisioningProfile          │
  Neither (SecurityConfig catch-all only) │ Approval, CsvMappingTemplate,│  4
                                          │ DirectoryBrowse, Schema      │
  Mixed within same controller            │ AccessReview (feature +      │  4
                                          │ manual superadmin check),    │
                                          │ User (feature for writes,    │
                                          │ nothing for reads), Group    │
                                          │ (same), ProvisioningProfile  │
                                          │ (mixed superadmin/admin)     │

Anti-patterns observed:

  1. Same URL hierarchy, different auth mechanisms.
     /api/v1/directories/{id}/users (POST) → @RequiresFeature(USER_CREATE)
     /api/v1/directories/{id}/users (GET)  → nothing
     /api/v1/directories/{id}/groups (POST) → @RequiresFeature(GROUP_CREATE_DELETE)
     /api/v1/directories/{id}/groups (GET)  → nothing

  2. Unvalidated directoryId in @PreAuthorize-only controllers.
     LifecyclePlaybookController takes @PathVariable UUID directoryId but
     doesn't use @DirectoryId or @RequiresFeature. Directory-level access
     is checked only in the service layer. If the service has a bug, the
     controller provides no safety net.

  3. Controllers with both directoryId and profileId but no scope reconciliation.
     ProvisioningProfileController routes like:
       /api/v1/directories/{directoryId}/profiles/{profileId}
     rely entirely on service-layer validation that profileId belongs to
     directoryId. No controller-level or aspect-level cross-validation.

  4. Manual ad-hoc authorization in one method of an otherwise annotation-driven
     controller (AccessReviewController.create — runtime isSuperadmin() check
     alongside @RequiresFeature on every other method).

  5. ApprovalController has ZERO authorization annotations on any of its 6
     endpoints, despite performing state-changing operations (approve, reject,
     updatePayload). All authorization is implicit via SecurityConfig catch-all
     + service-layer checks.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
15. RECOMMENDED STRUCTURAL IMPROVEMENT
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

If one structural change were made, it should be:

  Standardize on @RequiresFeature as the SINGLE authorization mechanism for
  all directory-scoped endpoints.

What this entails:

  a) Add feature keys for read operations.
     New keys: USER_VIEW, GROUP_VIEW (or a single DIRECTORY_BROWSE).
     Apply @RequiresFeature to search(), get(), browse() endpoints.
     This closes the "unprotected reads" gap and makes the READ_ONLY role
     meaningful at the feature level.

  b) Add feature keys for currently ungated operations.
     New keys: APPROVAL_MANAGE, PLAYBOOK_EXECUTE, PLAYBOOK_MANAGE.
     Apply to ApprovalController, LifecyclePlaybookController.
     Replace @PreAuthorize on playbook endpoints with @RequiresFeature.

  c) Add a startup-time scan that rejects unannotated endpoints.
     A Spring ApplicationListener<ContextRefreshedEvent> that introspects all
     @RequestMapping methods under /api/v1/directories/** and fails startup if
     any lack @RequiresFeature. This makes the "forget to annotate" failure
     mode impossible.

       @Component
       public class AuthAnnotationValidator implements
               ApplicationListener<ContextRefreshedEvent> {
           @Override
           public void onApplicationEvent(ContextRefreshedEvent event) {
               // Scan all @RequestMapping methods in directory controllers
               // Throw if any lacks @RequiresFeature
           }
       }

  d) Add a request-scoped permission cache.
     On the first @RequiresFeature check in a request, load the admin's
     profile roles and feature overrides into a request-scoped bean. Reuse
     on subsequent checks in the same request. This collapses 3N queries
     (where N = permission checks per request) down to 3.

       @RequestScope
       @Component
       public class PermissionContext {
           private List<AdminProfileRole> profileRoles;
           private List<AdminFeaturePermission> featureOverrides;
           // Lazy-loaded, cached for request duration
       }

  e) Add the missing index.
     Migration V_next:
       CREATE INDEX idx_apr_admin ON admin_profile_roles(admin_account_id);

  f) Replace over-fetched query.
     Change findAllByAdminAccountId() call in requireFeature() to:
       existsByAdminAccountIdAndBaseRole(adminId, BaseRole.ADMIN)

  g) Document the feature permission matrix.
     Generate from @RequiresFeature annotations at build time (annotation
     processor or test that outputs a markdown table). This gives superadmins
     a reference for what each feature key actually gates.

Result: a single authorization mechanism, enforced at startup, cached per
request, with a documented permission matrix. The three-mechanism ambiguity
disappears. New endpoints get a compiler-like check. Performance improves.
Security audits become a matter of reviewing one enum and one annotation.

Estimated effort: 2-3 days (can be done alongside or after the remediation
steps in section 9).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
16. EVALUATION SUMMARY
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

  ┌─────────────────────┬───────────┬────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ Dimension           │ Rating    │ Key issue                                  │
  ├─────────────────────┼───────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Robustness          │ Moderate  │ Three competing auth mechanisms with no    │
  │                     │           │ enforced convention; catch-all too         │
  │                     │           │ permissive; READs unprotected             │
  ├─────────────────────┼───────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Ease of application │ Mixed     │ @RequiresFeature is ergonomic; everything │
  │                     │           │ else requires tribal knowledge of which    │
  │                     │           │ mechanism to use where                     │
  ├─────────────────────┼───────────┼────────────────────────────────────────────┤
  │ Efficiency          │ Adequate  │ 3 uncached DB queries per request; missing │
  │                     │           │ index on hottest path; over-fetch in       │
  │                     │           │ base-role fallback                         │
  └─────────────────────┴───────────┴────────────────────────────────────────────┘

The authorization model's strongest asset is the @RequiresFeature + FeatureKey
pattern. Its weakest aspect is that this pattern isn't the only one — two other
mechanisms coexist without clear boundaries, making the system harder to audit,
extend, and trust. The recommended path forward is to promote @RequiresFeature
to the single standard, enforce it at startup, and cache it per request.
